## The First Dragonborn

Long before **Alduin** was defeated at the Throat of the World, long before the ancient Nords rose up against the tyranny of the dragons, a man was born with an unprecedented gift. **Miraak** was the first **Dovahkiin** — the first mortal to possess the soul of a dragon within a man's body. This power, granted by **Akatosh** himself according to tradition, gave him the ability to absorb the souls of dragons and wield the **Thu'um** with supernatural ease.

In Miraak's time, dragons ruled **Tamriel** as absolute tyrants. The **Dragon Cult** dominated Nordic society, with dragon priests serving as intermediaries between mortals and their winged masters. Humans lived in servitude, building monumental temples to the glory of their oppressors and sacrificing their own children to appease draconic hunger.

Miraak served as a dragon priest on the island of **Solstheim**, one of the most powerful of his generation. His mastery of the Thu'um was unmatched among mortals, and the dragons themselves acknowledged his exceptional power. But where others would have seen this power as a tool for better service, Miraak saw an opportunity to free himself from servitude.

## The Temptation of Hermaeus Mora

It was during this period of questioning that **Hermaeus Mora** — the Daedric Prince of forbidden knowledge and forgotten secrets — turned his attention toward Miraak. The Gardener of Men recognized in the Dragonborn a perfect instrument: a mortal powerful enough to challenge the dragons, ambitious enough to desire absolute power, and arrogant enough to believe he could use a Daedric Prince without becoming his slave.

Hermaeus Mora offered Miraak forbidden knowledge, lost Shouts, secrets of power that even the dragons did not know. In exchange, Miraak was to serve the Daedric Prince and extend his influence over Nirn. The Dragonborn accepted, convinced he could steer the relationship to his advantage. It was the first of his many errors in judgment.

The **Black Books** that Mora taught Miraak were of terrifying power, capable of bending the will of mortals and even affecting draconic minds. Armed with this knowledge, Miraak began plotting his rebellion — not to free humanity from draconic oppression, but to replace the dragons at the apex of the power hierarchy.

## The Betrayal

Miraak's betrayal was not an act of liberation but of personal conquest. When he turned against his dragon masters, it was not on behalf of the human slaves suffering under the draconic yoke. It was out of pure ambition — a desire to rule where he had once served. His revolt was that of a tyrant-in-waiting against established tyrants.

Miraak used his Dovahkiin powers to absorb the souls of the dragons he slew, growing stronger with each victory. The dragons sent to punish him fell one after another, their essences consumed by the traitor. On Solstheim, he built a temple to his own glory, enslaving the local populations with the same brutality the dragons had shown before him.

His Shouts could split the earth and bend mountains. The **Black Book** Word of submission he had learned from Hermaeus Mora allowed him to control the minds of mortals, turning them into devoted servants without will of their own. Miraak was building an empire — a kingdom where a single Dovahkiin would rule over men as the dragons had done before him.

## The Duel with Vahlok

The dragons could not tolerate this defiance. They sent **Vahlok** — another dragon priest of exceptional power — to destroy the traitor. The duel between Miraak and Vahlok was so violent it reshaped the geography of Solstheim. Their Shouts clashed with a force that split the earth, and the island itself nearly came apart from the intensity of the battle.

The combat lasted for days, each adversary unleashing ever more devastating Shouts. Witnesses speak of storms of fire and ice, of earthquakes caused by Words of Power, of entire sections of terrain torn up and hurled into the sky. Solstheim was separated from the mainland by the violence of this confrontation, becoming the island we know today.

Vahlok, later called the **Guardian**, eventually gained the upper hand. Miraak, wounded and weakened, was on the verge of defeat. But at the crucial moment, **Hermaeus Mora** intervened, tearing his champion from the mortal world and transporting him to **Apocrypha**, his realm of Oblivion. The Daedric Prince was not about to let his investment be destroyed so easily.

## Imprisonment in Apocrypha

**Apocrypha** became Miraak's gilded prison. Hermaeus Mora's realm is an infinite labyrinth of books and scrolls, an ocean of knowledge stretching as far as the eye can see. For a mind as hungry for knowledge and power as Miraak's, it was both paradise and hell: an eternity surrounded by secrets, yet no one over whom to exercise dominion.

For millennia, Miraak wandered through Apocrypha, reading, learning, scheming. His power continued to grow, fed by the infinite knowledge of Mora's realm. But he remained a prisoner, unable to return to **Nirn** without the permission of his daedric jailer. The arrogance that had driven him to believe he could manipulate a Daedric Prince turned against him with cruel irony.

Hermaeus Mora kept Miraak alive for his own reasons. The first Dovahkiin was too valuable a tool to destroy — a weapon held in reserve for future use. And when, in the **Fourth Era**, another Dragonborn appeared in Skyrim, Mora finally saw the opportunity to set his plans in motion, pitting his two champions against each other in a game whose rules only he knew.

## The Legacy of Betrayal

The story of Miraak illustrates a recurring theme in the lore of Tamriel: the danger of power without wisdom and ambition without limits. The first Dovahkiin had received an unprecedented divine gift, and he chose to use it solely for his own glorification. His betrayal freed no one; it merely replaced one tyranny with another.

Ironically, it was the revolt of ordinary mortals — led later by heroes such as **Hakon**, **Gormlaith**, and **Felldir** — that truly freed humanity from the draconic yoke. These warriors, who possessed no dragon's soul, accomplished through courage and sacrifice what Miraak, with all his power, had never even attempted: to free their people.

On Solstheim, the stones of his temple still stand, and the Black Books he carved into rock continue to exert their influence over weak minds. Miraak's shadow stretches across the millennia, a reminder that the first Dragonborn was not a hero but a tyrant, and that the greatest power is worthless without the will to use it in the service of others.
